{"id":"1007.2537","submitter":"Fathi Namouni","authors":"Fathi Namouni","title":"The fate of moons of close-in giant exoplanets","comments":"4 pages, 2 figures, Astrophysical Journal Letters, in press","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/2041-8205/719/2/L145","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.EP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We show that the fate of moons of a close-in giant planet is mainly\ndetermined by the migration history of the planet in the protoplanetary disk.\nAs the planet migrates in the disk from beyond the snow line towards a\nmulti-day period orbit, the formed and forming moons become unstable as the\nplanet's sphere of influence shrinks. Disk-driven migration is faster than the\nmoons' tidal orbital evolution. Moons are eventually ejected from around\nclose-in exoplanets or forced into collision with them before tides from the\nstar affect their orbits. If moons are detected around close-in exoplanets,\nthey are unlikely to have been formed in situ, instead they were captured from\nthe protoplanetary disk on retrograde orbits around the planets.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 15 Jul 2010 12:10:18 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-05-19"}
